Create a scatterplot of price vs x using ggplot syntax.

ggplot(aes(x=x, y=price), data=diamonds) +
      geom_point()

ggplot(aes(x=x, y=price), data=diamonds) +
      geom_point(alpha=1/20, position = position_jitter(h=0), color = 'orange')



What are the observations about the scatterplot of price vs.x?
There is an exponential relationship between price and x. Greater activity in x-axis starting from 4 to 7. Price with values less than 7,500 has a greater activity for x between 4 and 7. Price with values more than 7,500 has an activity for x between 7 and 9.

Create a scatterplot of price vs.volume (xyz). This is a very rough approximation for a dismondss volume. Create a new variable for volumn in the diamonds data frame. This will be useful in a later exercise.

diamonds$volume <- diamonds$x*diamonds$y*diamonds$z
range(diamonds$volume)
## [1]    0.000 3840.598
ggplot(data=diamonds, aes(x=volume, y=price)) +
      geom_point(alpha=1/100,  
                 color ='orange')


What are your observations from the price vs.volume scatterplot? Some volumes are zero. There is an expensive diamond with price close to 4,000. There is not significant activity in a volume greater than 400. Most of the prices are below 10,000.

You can find out how many diamonds have 0 volume by using count(diamonds$volume == 0). The count function comes with the plyr package. Note: If you ran the count function from plyr, you need to unload the plyr package detach(package:plyr, unload=TRUE) The plyr will conflict with the dplyr package in later esxercises.

  • It does not work: count(diamonds$volume == 0) It gives error: Error in UseMethod(group_by_) : no applicable method for group_by_ applied to an object of class logical
  • It does not work: detach(package:plyr, unload=TRUE) gives error: Error in detach(package:plyr, unload = TRUE) : invalid name argument


What is the correlation of price and volume? Exclude diamonds that have a volume of 0 or that are greater than or equal to 800?

Subset the data to exclude diamonds with a volume greater than or equal to 800. Also, exclude diamonds with a volume of 0. Adjust the transparency of the points and add a linear model to the plot. Do you think this would be a useful model to estimate of price of diamonds? Why or why not? A 0.92 correlation is very strong which is not a good thing. The correlation was an artifact of the nature of the variable. One was really a super set of the other (see plots below).


Create subset that exclude diamonds with a volume greater than or equal to 800.

diamondsNewSubset = subset(diamonds,volume != 0 & volume<800)
ggplot(data=diamondsNewSubset, aes(x=volume, y=price)) +
      geom_point(alpha=1/100) + 
      geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Reducing x-axis from 0 to 400. However, there is an empty space after the 400 volume.The next plot will display limits much better by using x_lim.

ggplot(data=diamondsNewSubset, aes(x=volume, y=price)) +
      geom_point(alpha=1/100) + 
      scale_x_discrete(breaks = seq(0,400,50)) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm")

The following graphic shows better the x-axis than the one above. Look how we replace xlim for scale_x_discrete.

ggplot(data=diamondsNewSubset, aes(x=volume, y=price)) +
      geom_point(alpha=1/100) + 
      xlim(0,400) +
      #scale_x_discrete(breaks = seq(0,400,50)) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Use the function dplyr package to create a new data frame containing info on diamonds by clarity.
Name the data frame diamondsByClarity The data frame should contain the following: (1) mean_price (2) median_price (3) min_price (4) max_price (5) n, where n is the number of diamonds in each level of clarity.

diamonds_By_Clarity <- group_by(diamonds, clarity)
calc_diamonds_By_clarity <- summarise(diamonds_By_Clarity, 
        mean_price = mean(price),
        median_price = median(price),  
        min_price = min(price),
        n = n())

What do you notice in each of the bar charts for mean price by clarity and mean price by color?
Mean price tends to decrease as clarity improves. This is how it works for mean price across cut:

diamonds_by_color <- group_by(diamonds, color)
diamonds_mp_by_color <- summarise(diamonds_by_color, mean_price = mean(price))
p3 <- barplot(diamonds_mp_by_color$mean_price)
